      <hedline>
        <hl1>Thoughts on Thinking</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bob Erickson letter agrees that people who grow up in different cultures think differently, and sees further link with how languages are written and read (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''How Culture Molds Habits of Thought,'' Dr. Richard Nisbett says that people who grow up in different cultures ''think differently.'' I agree.</p>
        <p>I discovered in my research that how we think could very well depend on how we learn to read.</p>
        <p>In the West we learn to read left to right; in Asia, up and down, down and up; in the Middle East, right to left.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''How Culture Molds Habits of Thought,'' Dr. Richard Nisbett says that people who grow up in different cultures ''think differently.'' I agree.</p>
        <p>I discovered in my research that how we think could very well depend on how we learn to read.</p>
        <p>In the West we learn to read left to right; in Asia, up and down, down and up; in the Middle East, right to left.</p>
        <p>This caused our brains to be hard-wired differently and thus think differently, as Dr. Nisbett's evidence suggests. My hat is off to him.</p>
        <p>BOB ERICKSON  Westtown, Pa.</p>
      </block>
